{
  "texts": [
    "These neurons process input data by applying weights 1 (scaling factors) and biases 2 (offsets) before passing the result through an activation function.",
    "Early models like the perceptron were capable of handling simple classification tasks by adjusting these parameters to minimize errors, as quantified by a loss function 3 (Terven, Cordova-Esparza, Ramirez-Pedraza, Chavez-Urbiola & Romero-Gonzalez, 2024) -a measure of the difference between predicted and actual outputs.",
    "However, these models were limited to linear decision boundaries and struggled with more complex, nonlinear problems.",
    "The introduction of the backpropagation algorithm (Werbos, 1974) marked a significant advancement, allowing neural networks to adjust weights and biases more effectively using gradient descent.",
    "This method calculates gradients of the loss function to iteratively update the network's parameters."
  ]
}